# Responsive Design Requirements

Always ensure websites are fully responsive and mobile-friendly. Follow these guidelines:

## HTML Requirements

- **Viewport meta tag**: Always include `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">` in the `<head>`
- **Semantic HTML**: Use semantic elements (`<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<footer>`)
- **Accessible structure**: Ensure proper heading hierarchy and ARIA labels when needed

## CSS Requirements

### Mobile-First Approach

```css
/* ✅ GOOD - Mobile-first */
.container {
  padding: 1rem;
  width: 100%;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    padding: 2rem;
    max-width: 1200px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
}

/* ❌ BAD - Desktop-first */
.container {
  padding: 2rem;
  max-width: 1200px;
}

@media (max-width: 767px) {
  .container {
    padding: 1rem;
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

### Responsive Breakpoints

Use standard breakpoints:
- **Mobile**: Default styles (no media query)
- **Tablet**: `@media (min-width: 768px)`
- **Desktop**: `@media (min-width: 1024px)`
- **Large Desktop**: `@media (min-width: 1280px)`

### Flexible Units

Prefer relative units over fixed pixels:
- Use `rem` or `em` for font sizes and spacing
- Use `%`, `vw`, `vh` for widths and heights
- Use `max-width` instead of fixed `width` for containers
- Avoid `px` for layout dimensions (okay for borders, shadows)

```css
/* ✅ GOOD */
.container {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 1200px;
  padding: 1.5rem;
  font-size: 1rem;
}

/* ❌ BAD */
.container {
  width: 1200px;
  padding: 24px;
  font-size: 16px;
}
```

### Flexible Layouts

- Use CSS Grid or Flexbox for layouts
- Avoid fixed heights that cause overflow
- Ensure content wraps gracefully on smaller screens
- Use `min-height` instead of fixed `height` when needed

### Images and Media

```css
/* ✅ GOOD - Responsive images */
img {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
  display: block;
}

/* ✅ GOOD - Responsive video/iframe */
video, iframe {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}
```

### Touch-Friendly Targets

- Minimum touch target size: 44×44px (iOS) or 48×48px (Material Design)
- Adequate spacing between interactive elements
- Avoid hover-only interactions on mobile

## Component Requirements (React/Vue/etc.)

- Use responsive CSS classes/utilities
- Conditionally render content based on screen size when appropriate
- Test components at different viewport sizes
- Use CSS-in-JS with responsive breakpoints

## Testing Checklist

Before completing any website, verify:
- [ ] Works on mobile (320px - 767px)
- [ ] Works on tablet (768px - 1023px)
- [ ] Works on desktop (1024px+)
- [ ] Text is readable without zooming
- [ ] Interactive elements are easily tappable
- [ ] No horizontal scrolling on any device
- [ ] Images scale appropriately
- [ ] Navigation works on all screen sizes

## Common Patterns

### Responsive Navigation

```css
/* Mobile: Hamburger menu */
@media (max-width: 767px) {
  .nav-menu {
    display: none;
  }
  .hamburger {
    display: block;
  }
}

/* Desktop: Full menu */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .nav-menu {
    display: flex;
  }
  .hamburger {
    display: none;
  }
}
```

### Responsive Grid

```css
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  gap: 1rem;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  }
}
```
